ame":"Stawell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Stowell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stowell","meanings":["English: habitational name from Stowell (Somerset), Stowell (Gloucestershire), East and West Stowell in Wilcot (Wiltshire), or Stawell (Somerset), all named with Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ + <i>wella</i> ‘well, spring, stream’. The surname was taken to the Isle of Man by 1511, from whence it migrated to Lancashire and Yorkshire."]}]},{"name":"Matthew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the Christian evangelist, author of the first gospel in the New Testament. His name is a form of the Hebrew name <i>Mattathia</i>, meaning ‘gift of God’, which is fairly common in the Old Testament, being rendered in the Authorized Version in a number of different forms: <i>Mattan(i)ah</i>, <i>Mattatha(h)</i>, <i>Mattithiah</i>, <i>Mattathias</i>, and so on. In the Authorized Version, the evangelist is regularly referred to as <i>Matthew</i>, while the apostle chosen to replace Judas Iscariot is distinguished as   Matthias .  A related name from the same Hebrew roots, but reversed, is   Jonathan .  Throughout the English-speaking world <i>Matthew</i> has been particularly popular since the 1970s."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathew","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Matthew ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":5,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":40,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and 